## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 | Replacement |
|-----|-------------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` signaling |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Can't be interrupted by cancellation | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |

**Bonus bug in original code:** If multiple items are enqueued rapidly, `Reset()` after `WaitOne()` can lose signals — only one item is dequeued per wake-up.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the original lost-signal bug)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                    {
                        _newEvent.Reset();
                        break;
                    }
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitHandle.WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation only
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — Cooperative cancellation. The loop checks `IsCancellationRequested` and `WaitHandle.WaitAny` unblocks when the token fires.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → `token.WaitHandle` in `WaitAny`** — The cancellation token's wait handle is included in the `WaitAny` array, so the blocked thread wakes immediately on cancel — no `Interrupt` needed.

3. **`ManualResetEvent.Reset()` race fix** — Reset is now inside the lock, only after confirming the queue is empty. All queued items are drained per wake-up.

4. **`IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are `IDisposable`. Leaking them causes timer/handle leaks.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| Calling `_thread.Abort()` as a "just in case" fallback | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 — there is no forcible kill |
| Not including `token.WaitHandle` in `WaitAny` | The thread stays blocked forever; `Stop()` hangs at `Join()` |
| Resetting the event outside the lock | Race condition: an `Enqueue` between `Reset` and the empty-check loses the signal |
